===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|vois|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno}} {{term|voiz|lang=xno}}, {{term|voys|lang=xno}}, {{term|voice|lang=xno}}, {{etyl|fro}} {{term|vois|lang=fro}}, {{term|voiz|lang=fro|tr=Modern {{etyl|fr|-}} {{term|voix|lang=fr}}}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|vocem|vōcem|lang=la}}, accusative form of {{etyl|la}} {{term|vox|vōx|voice|lang=la}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|wek-||wekw-|to utter, speak|lang=en}}. Cognate with Sanskrit [[वच्]] (to say, to speak), German ''[[erwähnen]]'' (to mention). Displaced native {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|steven||voice|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|stefn|lang=ang}} (see {{l|en|steven|steven}}), [[Middle English]] ''[[rouste#Middle English|rouste]]'' "voice" from Old Norse ''[[raust#Old Norse|raust]]'', and [[Middle English]] ''[[rearde#Middle English|rearde]]'' "voice" from [[Old English]] ''[[reord|reord]]''. Compare [[advocate]], [[advowson]], [[avouch]], [[convoke]], [[epic]], [[vocal]], [[vouch]], [[vowel]].

